To reproduce:
```
DELETE test

PUT test

POST test/_search
{
  "aggs": {
    "my_terms": {
      "terms": {
        "script": {
          "source": "10"
        },
        "value_type": "number"
      }
    }
  }
}
```
The error message is 
```
{
  "error" : {
    "root_cause" : [
      {
        "type" : "x_content_parse_exception",
        "reason" : "[8:23] [terms] failed to parse field [value_type]"
      }
    ],
    "type" : "x_content_parse_exception",
    "reason" : "[8:23] [terms] failed to parse field [value_type]",
    "caused_by" : {
      "type" : "illegal_argument_exception",
      "reason" : "[valueType] must not be null: [my_terms]"
    }
  },
  "status" : 400
}
```
Which is confusing because if shows up the moment a user actually adds `value_type`.

The error is caused by excessive [leniency in one place](https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch/blob/6c030dc8b8fa08843bdf4bbe2644d0538f322d52/server/src/main/java/org/elasticsearch/search/aggregations/support/ValueType.java#L118-L120) combine with [excessive strictness in another](https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch/blob/9f165bd44ee77a188b3c4dee833e624d906d5911/server/src/main/java/org/elasticsearch/search/aggregations/support/ValuesSourceAggregationBuilder.java#L257-L261).

**Elasticsearch version** (`bin/elasticsearch --version`):

Running on docker with `docker run -p 9200:9200 -p 9300:9300 -e "discovery.type=single-node" docker.elastic.co/elasticsearch/elasticsearch:7.6.2`

```
